# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bradken
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bradken/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:bradken/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:bradken/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:bradken/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:bradken/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:bradken/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:bradken/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:bradken/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:bradken/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:bradken/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:bradken/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:bradken/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:bradken/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The rough boundaries of Alexandria are Botany Road to the east, Gardeners Road to the south, Mitchell Road and Sydney Park to the west, and Boundary Road to the north.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] It is approximately 3.5 km south of Central station.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The Parish of Alexandria was established in 1835.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The naming of Alexandria and neighbouring Waterloo commemorates the famous British Empire military and naval victories over Napoleon – the Battles of Alexandria and Waterloo.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The Iron Duke Hotel in Alexandria is itself named after the Duke of Wellington, as is Wellington Street in Waterloo.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] It was thought Alexandria may have been named after Princess Alexandra, Queen consort of King Edward VII, however, Alexandra was born on 1 December 1844 and the parish's naming predates the birth of Alexandra by six years.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] In 1868, the Municipality of Alexandria was formed, after separating from Waterloo.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The former Alexandria Town Hall is in Garden Street.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Land for the building was acquired in 1879; the building was designed by Ferdinand Reuss Snr and completed in 1881.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Major alterations took place over the years, right up to 1928.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The building is listed on the New South Wales State Heritage Register.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] By 1943, Alexandria was the largest industrial district in Australia, and known as the "Birmingham of Australia", with everything from bricks to aeroplanes manufactured in 550 factories in just 1,000 acres (4.0 km2).
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The municipality was abolished upon merger into the City of Sydney in 1949, along with Darlington, Erskineville, Newtown, Redfern, Waterloo, Paddington and The Glebe.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] In 1968, the boundaries were changed again and Alexandria was part of a new municipality, South Sydney Council.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] South Sydney was brought back into the City of Sydney in 1982 and then became separate again under the City of Sydney Act of 1988.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] In 2004, Alexandria moved back into the City of Sydney, when the City of Sydney was merged with the City of South Sydney.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The former Alexandria tram line opened in 1902 as a single-track electric line that was duplicated in 1910.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The line branched off from the Botany line at the junction of Henderson and Botany Roads in Alexandria.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The line proceeded down Henderson Road then swung left into Mitchell Road.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] A turn-back was provided at Ashmore Road (near Erskineville Oval) for short working.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The line turned right into the present day Sydney Park Road (then known as an extension of Mitchell Road) before terminating at the junction with the Cook's River line at the Princes Highway near St Peters railway station.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Services operated from Circular Quay in a route similar to the Botany line as far as the Henderson Road junction.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Transit Systems route 308 generally follows the route as far as St Peters station.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] At the 2021 census, there were 9,649 people living in Alexandria.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] At the 2016 census, Alexandria had a population of 8,262.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people made up 1.8% of the population.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The most common ancestries in Alexandria were Australian 31.6%, English 24.3%, Irish 13.6%, Chinese 10.1% and Scottish 9.9%.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The most common other countries of birth were England 5.1%, New Zealand 3.3%, China (excludes SARs and Taiwan) 2.6%, the United States 1.4% and Indonesia 1.2%.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] 74.1% of people spoke only English at home.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Other languages spoken at home included Mandarin 3.1%, Spanish 2.0%, Cantonese 1.9%, Portuguese 1.0% and Indonesian 1.0%.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The most common responses for religion in Alexandria were No Religion 57.2%, Catholic 16.4%, Anglican 5.0% and Buddhism 3.0%.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] 65.2% of residences were flats and 29.0% were semi-detached, row or terrace house, townhouse etc.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Alexandria is a largely industrial suburb with medium to high density residential areas.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The suburb was once mostly terraced housing, that was demolished for light industrial use and warehousing which continues to this day.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Pockets of quiet residential areas remain along the northern boundary of the suburb, adjoining Erskineville and Waterloo.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] One of the landing points of the trans-Pacific submarine telecommunications cable, the Southern Cross Cable, is located in the suburb.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Alexandria is part of the Green Square district, in the north east of the suburb, which is undergoing gentrification.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] This involves an urban renewal project that is constructing modern retail, business and medium-high density residential developments.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Established in September 2009, its main purpose was to meet the community demand for local markets, providing fine produce and a venue for local handmade crafts.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The children's activities kept the little ones entertained with face painting and a kids zoo.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] It was open every Sunday 10am - 3pm at O'Riordan St Alexandria however, it has unfortunately been temporarily closed.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Alexandria is serviced by Transdev John Holland routes to the Sydney central business district.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Alexandria is also close to multiple railway stations.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] To the east, Waterloo railway station is serviced by the Metro North West & Bankstown Line, while Green Square railway station is serviced by the Airport & South Line.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] To the west, Erskineville railway station and St Peters railway station are serviced by either the Airport & South Line or the Eastern Suburbs & Illawarra Line.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] As of 2026, at Mitchell Road, Ashmore Street and Harley Street there is a proposal for new traffic signals.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Alexandria is transited by the McEvoy Street state road (Alexandria to Moore Park Project), which also passes through Waterloo.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The Southern Arterial Route terminates in north Alexandria, and was originally proposed to run through Alexandria on Wyndham Street.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Sydney Park is a large recreational area on the western border.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Alexandria Park and McKell Playground are situated on Buckland Street.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Tennis courts and a cricket oval are located here.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Erskineville Oval is just over the western border.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] Erskineville Oval is the home ground of the Alexandria Rovers junior rugby league team.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The Alexandria Dukes Rugby Football Club play in the New South Wales Suburban Rugby Union competition and will again contest the Meldrum Cup in 2014.
[src:bradken/alexandria-new-south-wales] The club rooms for the Dukes are at the Iron Duke Hotel.
[src:bradken/astemo] The company name was changed from **Hitachi Astemo, Ltd.** to Astemo, Ltd. on April 1, 2025.
[src:bradken/astemo] Astemo was established in January 2021 as a global automotive components manufacturer through the business merger of Hitachi Automotive Systems, Keihin Corporation, Showa Corporation, and Nissin Kogyo.
[src:bradken/astemo] The name "Astemo" stands for "Advanced Sustainable Technologies for Mobility", reflecting the company's focus on technologies related to connected, autonomous, shared and electric mobility.
[src:bradken/astemo] Astemo develops automotive technologies aligned with the industry trends of connectivity, autonomous systems and electrification, with a focus on both passenger and motorcycle applications.
[src:bradken/astemo] Astemo's ownership structure includes major stakes from both Hitachi, Ltd. and Honda Motor Co., Ltd., each holding 40%, with JIC Capital holding the remaining 20%.
[src:bradken/astemo] While Astemo includes former Honda-affiliated parts manufacturers, it also maintains business relationships with Nissan Motor Co., reflecting Hitachi's historical ties to the Nissan Group.
[src:bradken/astemo] In December 2025, Honda announced it would acquire an additional 21% of Astemo shares from Hitachi.
[src:bradken/astemo] As a result, the shareholding structure of Astemo will change to 61% for Honda, 20% for JIC, and 19% for Hitachi.
[src:bradken/astemo] Astemo has expanded its research and development activities in electric powertrains, advanced driver-assistance systems, and in-vehicle software.
[src:bradken/astemo] These efforts support its strategic focus on electrification and autonomous mobility.
[src:bradken/astemo] The company has also pursued partnerships and vertical integration to address industry competition and supply chain challenges.
[src:bradken/astemo] In December 2024, the Government of Cantabria awarded the Hitachi Astemo Buelna plant a €1 million grant through SODERCAN’s competitive programme for major industrial competitiveness projects.
[src:bradken/astemo] The funding supports a €5 million experimental development project focused on advanced braking systems, to be completed over 18 months.
[src:bradken/astemo] This initiative underlines the region’s strategic support for automotive innovation and sustainability efforts.
[src:bradken/astemo] Astemo develops components for electric and autonomous vehicles, with a focus on integration of key systems such as power control units, motors, inverters, and software-defined vehicle platforms.
[src:bradken/astemo] The company also emphasizes model-based systems engineering and virtual validation to shorten development timelines and reduce prototyping costs.
[src:bradken/astemo] In 2023, Astemo announced a ¥15.3 billion (~US $100 million) expansion of its Berea, Kentucky plant to support its electrification business.
[src:bradken/astemo] In July 2025, Astemo announced a £100 million investment in its Horwich manufacturing facility in Bolton, Greater Manchester.
[src:bradken/astemo] The project will establish a new production line dedicated to electric vehicle (EV) inverters, making the site the only facility in the United Kingdom with this production capability.
[src:bradken/astemo] As of 2025, Astemo operates over 100 business sites globally, including manufacturing plants, R&D centers and regional offices across Asia, Europe and the Americas.
[src:bradken/astemo] Astemo's facilities span over 25 countries, including sites in Mexico, France, Brazil, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:bradken/astemo] A complete list is available on the Astemo Global Network.
[src:bradken/astemo] In September 2025, *CBS News* and *The Detroit News* reported that Astemo planned to establish a regional headquarters in Wixom, Michigan, as part of a $95 million investment expected to create about 200 jobs.
[src:bradken/astemo] Hitachi Astemo sponsors Team Penske in NTT IndyCar Series in the U.S.A.
[src:bradken/astemo] Astemo also sponsors Real Racing in the Super GT GT500 class and S.I.
[src:bradken/astemo] RACING in the MFJ All Japan Road Race Championship Series.
[src:bradken/astemo] Astemo owns the Japanese women's volleyball team "Hitachi Astemo Rivale" and sponsors Mie Honda Heat, a Japanese rugby union team based in Suzuka City.
[src:bradken/astemo] On December 21, 2021, Hitachi Astemo admitted to falsifying inspection data on brake and suspension components.
[src:bradken/astemo] Over 50,000 instances of improper testing were identified, dating back to 2003.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The ***Australian Financial Review*** (AFR) is an Australian compact daily newspaper with a focus on business, politics and economic affairs.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The newspaper is based in Sydney, New South Wales, and has been published continuously since its founding in 1951.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] It is currently owned by Nine Entertainment.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The *AFR* is published in tabloid format six times a week, and provides 24/7 coverage through its website and mobile app.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In November 2019, the *AFR* reached 2.647 million Australians through both print and digital mediums according to *Mumbrella*.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The *Australian Financial Review* started as a print-only weekly newspaper in 1951, before changing to a bi-weekly in 1961, and a daily newspaper in 1963.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The paper now publishes multiple magazines and a supplementary weekend paper, which was launched in 1995.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In that same year, the *AFR* website was also released, which helped to expand its readership base across all media.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The *AFR*, along with most of Fairfax Media, was purchased by Nine Entertainment in 2018.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The *Australian Financial Review* newspaper started as a weekly publication in 1951, published by John Fairfax & Sons.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The paper's main objective was to inform the Australian public on business life and news.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In 1961, the *AFR* converted to a bi-weekly, and then established itself as the first daily newspaper by 1963.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Despite other newspapers claiming the title of the first daily national paper, Maxwell Newton was the editor in charge of taking the *Financial Review* from a bi-weekly to the first daily national paper.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] During 1961–62, the *AFR's* primary competitor was The *Australian Financial Times*, which was in operation for less than 12 months.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In the 1960s and 1970s, the *AFR* developed a strong readership amongst a specialist business audience due to its neutral stance on domestic government policies.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In the 1970s, despite the *AFR's* reputation as a national business daily, many saw it as the primary competitor for *The Australian* given its high proportion of readers in the AB demographic.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In 1995, Fairfax launched the *Australian Financial Review Magazine* in response to its growing readership across a wide-ranging audience.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The magazine was published to cover topics other than business including leisure, politics, travel, sports, fashion, and other peripheral topics.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In December 2019, the magazine recorded an average issue readership of 326,000.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Since its launch in 1995, the *AFR Magazine* has won the 'Best Newspaper Inserted Magazine' (2013-2019), 'Newspaper Inserted Brand of the Year' (2019) and Mumbrella's 'Special Issue of the Year' (2019).
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The magazine's founding was followed by the launch of the *AFR*'s website in the same year, which started as a free online source of financial news.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In 1997, the *AFR* launched its *Weekend Edition* which extended the paper's publications into the weekend, with an explicit focus of targeting the growing readership base by providing news articles outside of the traditional finance setting.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In 2016, the *AFR* launched mobile and iPad compatible applications to provide its digital subscribers more accessibility to its news platform.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] This was aimed at allowing cross-platform accessibility without having to download two separate applications across different device platforms.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The application carries similar features to the website including sections such as: Street Talk and Rear Window.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The product management team decided to revamp the app due to the wide uptake of smartphones in the Australian market, and to improve their user-interface experience.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The UTS Business School was the launch partner for the app, providing logistical advice on the app's delivery.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The app's subscription price is included in the 'all premium digital subscription' bundle.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The *Australian Financial Review* has grown its product offerings since its beginnings as a finance newsroom.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] It has consistently been well received by the journalism sector as one of the most high-quality newsrooms across Australia.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Since the 2000s, the *AFR* has launched *BOSS* (magazine for business leadership and strategy) and the *Sophisticated Traveller* magazine.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In 2019, the *Australian Financial Review* recorded double-digit subscriber growth, as it continued to market its newspaper as the driver of Australian business-people's success and ambitions.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In 2020, due to the newspaper company's expansion efforts across different readership bases, the *AFR* reached 2.647m Australians a month.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The *AFR* first introduced its paywall in 2006, charging online users to view its articles – a payment model that had not yet been utilised by any other Australian newspaper firm.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The switch to a paywall was done because the newspaper company thought it could further monetise its niche business audience who could afford it.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Following this change, the *AFR* continued to adjust the pricing of its subscription due to low subscriber growth.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In 2011, it newly introduced a freemium paywall in which only a small portion of articles were free.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] It has been noted that the *AFR's* website locks approximately 86% of its online content behind a paywall, higher than its closest competitor the *National Business Review*.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] This was aimed at increasing its digital readership which in 2011 amounted to 6,000 subscribers.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In addition, it was later determined that the *AFR's* failures in attracting online subscribers was due to its paywall being too expensive.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Its 2012 price of $59 was notably higher than other international mastheads, including the *New York Times* which was priced at $37.84.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] As a result, the *AFR* has since lowered its digital subscription price to $29.50.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In October 2022, Nine announced that it would discontinue printing the AFR in Tasmania, with copies to instead be flown in from Melbourne on the following day.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In May 2024, printed editions of the AFR were discontinued in Western Australia, which Nine attributed to an increase in printing costs by its competitor Seven West Media, the owner of the only suitable printing press in Western Australia.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In May 2025, Nine Entertainment considered reintroducing printed editions into Western Australia after Post Newspapers opened a printing plant in Perth.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Across the AFR group, the team does not only publish newspapers.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The Financial Review Rich List aims to compile an annual ranking of the wealthiest Australian citizens.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The list was first published in the *BRW Magazine* in 1984.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Since its beginnings, the compilation of the list and its publishing have been taken over by the *AFR*, now being published annually in the *Australian Financial Review Magazine* and on the afr.com.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Along with the names of the richest people, the list explicates the person or family's net worth and provides a short summary on the business activities and sector they are engaged in.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The valuations are conducted by utilising a mix of publicly available information and private consultations.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In 2019, the cut-off for making the Rich List was $472m AUD.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In 2020, the cut-off was raised to $540m AUD.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] The newspaper has also been labelled as one of the propagators of radical liberalism during the 1970s–80s, shaping the policy debate surrounding market deregulation at that time.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] This was in line with the overarching political stance of all Fairfax Holdings owned newspapers, including the *Sydney Morning Herald*, which in the 1970s was also right-leaning in its political views.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] In the wake of the 1987 stock market crash, the Australian news media sector was blamed for overlooking corporate corruption and wrongdoings, while publishing mainly favourable news articles handed to them from corporate PR teams.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Also during this time, *The National* Times which was Australia's leading financial investigative journalism newspaper, shut down after the stock market crash.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Therefore, during the 2000s, following the financial market failures and economic downturn of the 1990s, the *AFR*'s reporting focus steered more towards business investigative journalism, scrutinising big corporations, government power and corruption.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] This was viewed as the *AFR* making reparations for its lack of scrutiny over the corporate sector in the lead-up to the stock market crash.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] One major factor that allowed the *AFR* to undertake deep corporate investigations was that it did not need advertising revenue to stay afloat – its cover price was sufficient.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] On the other hand, all other daily mastheads needed company advertising to stay profitable.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] This afforded the *AFR*'s editors the flexibility to pursue and publish news articles that shed a negative light on major companies without needing to be concerned about its financial impacts.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] During the controversial 2013 tax debate regarding taxes for "extraordinary" profits generated by mining companies, major mastheads from regions with high mining interests had almost fourfold the number of negative articles compared to positive articles.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] *The Australian*, the biggest national daily, had a large number of both positive and negative articles, but had a limited number of neutral articles.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Out of all the daily mastheads, the *AFR* published the most articles surrounding the tax debate and also the most number of neutral articles.
[src:bradken/australian-financial-review] Government officials including Cyprus president Nikos Christodoulides and European lawmakers began responding to the investigation's findings in less than 24 hours, calling for reforms and launching probes.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] In 1911 John McGrath began to sell motor vehicles.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] It operated the first public garage in New South Wales.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] The company held motor vehicle franchises for many makes of cars.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] In 1929, it diversified into importing steel and engineering equipment.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] In the mid-1930s production of drop forgings commenced with motor dealerships opening in other states.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] In the early 1940s, the largest forging plant in Australia was opened in Lidcombe, producing forgings for the aircraft and munitions industry.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] Activities expanded and diversified to include general engineering.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] In February 1951 **John McGrath Industries Limited** was listed on the Sydney Stock Exchange.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] It was renamed Australian National Industries in 1956.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] Having acquired a 20% shareholding in ANI, Kerry Packer's Australian Consolidated Press (ACP) launched a takeover offer in April 1989.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] ACP gained control with a 48% shareholding in June 1989.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] In 1991, ACP sold its struggling European waste management company ABT to ANI for $2 million, a decision which was not disclosed to ANI shareholders.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] Two weeks later, Packer, who had already reduced his shareholding in ANI from 48% to 30%, sold his remaining stake, making a $200 million profit.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] ABT had signed a contract to build a $150 million waste treatment facility in Madrid which some observers thought was more likely to cost about $400 million.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] In 2006, it was estimated that the final losses from ANI's venture into European waste management approached $1 billion.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] In 1997, Bob Ellicott QC conducted an independent enquiry into the circumstances surrounding the sale of ABT to ANI, but his report was never made public by the corporate regulator, the Australian Securities & Investments Commission, because the ANI board claimed it was defamatory.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] In October 1998, Evans Deakin Industries, that held a 5% shareholding in ANI, announced its intention to launch a takeover offer.
[src:bradken/australian-national-industries] In December 1998, Smorgon Steel launched a counter takeover offer that was successful, with ANI delisted from the Australian Securities Exchange on 17 March 1999.
[src:bradken/bradken] In 1919/1920, BHP steelworks employees, General Manager Leslie Bradford and Chief Mechanical Engineer Jim Kendall and a group of their friends backed a racehorse named Jack Findlay that completed a remarkable sequence of five wins.
[src:bradken/bradken] With each win the group rolled-over their bets and by 24 January 1920 they had won a small fortune pledging their winnings to start a steel foundry business.
[src:bradken/bradken] On 28 April 1920, Bradford and Kendall used their winnings to establish the Alloy Steel Syndicate and build a steel foundry in Alexandria, Sydney.
[src:bradken/bradken] The syndicate was incorporated as Bradford Kendall Limited on 20 March 1922.
[src:bradken/bradken] In 1926 Bradford Kendall began to manufacture railway couplers and undercarriages.
[src:bradken/bradken] In the 1930s it entered the export market, manufacturing dredge buckets for use in Malaysia.
[src:bradken/bradken] In 1948 the company was listed on the Sydney Stock Exchange.
[src:bradken/bradken] In the 1950s foundries were established in Adelaide, Brisbane, Fremantle and Wodonga.
[src:bradken/bradken] In 1970 a foundry was established in Port Hedland.
[src:bradken/bradken] In December 1974 the company changed its name to Bradken.
[src:bradken/bradken] By 1978 Bradken was controlled by Australian National Industries (ANI) and Comeng.
[src:bradken/bradken] In 1982 ANI became the sole shareholder.
[src:bradken/bradken] In October 1990, the head office moved from Alexandra to Mayfield West.
[src:bradken/bradken] In 1995 the business was rebranded as ANI Bradken.
[src:bradken/bradken] The business was included in the January 1999 purchase of ANI by Smorgon Steel who sold the business to Castle Harlan Australian Mezzanine Partners.
[src:bradken/bradken] In August 2004 Bradken was relisted on the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:bradken/bradken] In November 2007 a new manufacturing facility opened in Xuzhou, China.
[src:bradken/bradken] In July 2009 the business of Americast Technologies in the United States was acquired.
[src:bradken/bradken] In July 2011 Norcast Wear Solutions in Canada and SwanMet in Malaysia were purchased.
[src:bradken/bradken] In March 2013 Bradken opened a greenfield foundry development in Xuzhou, China following the construction of a manufacturing facility on the site in 2007.
[src:bradken/bradken] In October 2016 Hitachi Construction Machinery launched a takeover offer for Bradken.
[src:bradken/bradken] The transaction was completed in May 2017.
[src:bradken/bradken] On June 10, 2021, it was announced that White Industries had acquired the Ipswich site operations, a strategic decision by its parent company Hitachi Manufacturing to move its operations to offshore facilities.
